 definition settings follow the same pattern as the message design document example.\n\nNow I'm checking each section against the source to identify what's been omitted. The overview section just references navigation links which are acceptable to leave out. The tool placement section strips cross-references but keeps the core content. The output file settings section lists all seven files with descriptions. The common settings section covers the single config file. I'm working through the environment settings section now to verify completeness. I'm checking sections s8 through s10 now. The component definition file section correctly notes when modifications are needed based on design document changes. For the input file reading settings, the excluded sheets note is preserved. Moving into the message design document reading configuration, I see XML code with configuration details and comments about data reading start rows and message ID retrieval keys. I'm seeing that the knowledge base strips out the XML comments but preserves all the actual property configurations, which is fine since the property names themselves are descriptive. Looking at s11 and s12, they follow the same pattern. The source document also notes that domain definitions, validation processing definitions, and data type definitions share the same configuration structure as the message design settings, so those are omitted from the examples. This note is actually decision-critical because it explicitly tells users that domain definitions, validation processing definitions, and data type definitions all follow the same configuration pattern as message design settings. Since the knowledge file doesn't include this guidance, users wouldn't know which loader class to use or how to structure these configurations, making this a significant omission for implementation. I'm realizing that the note about domain/validation/datatype definitions using the same DefinitionFileLoader configuration as messageDesignLoader is actually important context—it's not just a documentation aside. This means when someone asks how to configure those loaders, I should point them to messageDesignLoader as the template since they all use the same structure. I initially marked this as a minor omission, but it's actually critical configuration guidance I should include.\n\nNow I'm doing a fabrication check against the source material to make sure everything I've documented is accurate. Going through each section: the content descriptions match exactly, the file listings are correct, the configuration keys are all accounted for with their examples preserved, and the guidance about when to modify settings aligns with what's in the source.\n\nI'm also verifying the RST document structure—checking that the heading hierarchy is correct with the title using overline/underline characters and the main sections (概要, ツール配置場所, 利用の準備) all at the same h2 level. I'm working through the RST heading hierarchy more carefully now. The structure uses different underline characters to denote levels, and I need to trace through which character corresponds to which heading depth based on the order they first appear in the document. Looking at the structure, I can see the next four sections are all h4 headings nested under the \"入力ファイル読み取り設定\" h3 section, covering different file input configurations for messages, tables, and code designs. This brings the total to 12 sections with a clear hierarchical organization where the preparation section acts as a container for the configuration subsections. I'm checking the completeness of hints for each section. Section 5 seems to have incomplete hints - I need to verify what information should be included there for the environment configuration file and component definition file entries. I'm checking the hints for s10 through s12 against the actual configuration content. S10 covers the key class names and properties like `DefinitionFileLoader` and `messageDesignColumnDefs`